      "text": "The 90s timeout fired on the broader user-folder scan. But I got something very useful — in the first Downloads scan, I noticed a much bigger AI Studio extract folder: `Google AI Studio-20260623T104922Z-3-005_extracted\\Google AI Studio\\` — that \"005\" not \"001\" — which suggests there are FIVE such extracted folders. Let me check what's in the \"001\" folder specifically for the photos that match the original Bairstow Eves inventory.\n\nWait, I also noticed in the output: `photo_1_2025-07-08_13-20-37.jpg` and similar — those are dated July 2025, way before March 2026, so they're unrelated to the inventory.\n\nLet me think differently. The user said \"the original report that was sent to richard and that then i like photocopied or sth\". \n\nMaybe \"photocopied\" doesn't literally mean a paper photocopy — it could mean \"took a copy of\" the PDF that Bairstow Eves emailed him. The original PDF from Bairstow Eves could be:\n\n1. An attachment in his email (we don't have email access)\n2. A file on the original device he used to receive it\n3. Somewhere on his system that we haven't searched\n\nLet me check the AI Studio extract folders more carefully. I noticed there are MULTIPLE extracted AI Studio folders (001, 005, etc.) — maybe one of them has the original inventory PDF or photos.\n\nActually wait, the date prefix `20260623T104922Z` is 23 June 2026 — that's when the AI Studio data was extracted. The content might span months.\n\nLet me list all the AI Studio extracted folders and look inside the one labeled \"001\" for any inventory PDFs or photos.\n\nAlso, I just realized — the user might have the original inventory scan as ONE OF THE PHOTOS in the AI Studio extracted data. The Gemini JSON I read earlier had `driveImage` references like `1eEWpuUtBf4d2tWgEccn6SzwH3g6in6R1` — these are Google Drive IDs for the images uploaded. Maybe in the \"005\" folder (which is the bigger one with more files), there are extracted images that include the inventory photos.\n\nLet me check what's in the AI Studio-005folder more carefully and look for any original inventory PDFs.",
