      "code": "{\"command\": \"python -c \\\"import zipfile, re; z = zipfile.ZipFile(r'C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Documents\\\\17 Gedling Street.docx'); doc = z.read('word/document.xml').decode('utf-8', errors='replace'); text = re.sub(r'<[^>]+>', ' ', doc); text = re.sub(r'\\\\s+', ' ', text); print(text[:5000])\\\"\", \"description\": \"Extract text from the docx\"}",
      "output": " BEDROOM – FRONT – UPSTAIRS R 2.WA1.ii Radiators to be tested , as not clearly marked as tested anywhere I have received the Gas Safety Record, which confirms the safety of the boiler and gas appliances. However, this does not confirm the functionality of the radiators themselves. Please arrange for a heating engineer to bleed or check over these radiators to ensure the central heating system is fully functional. Marked as \"Good\" is an opinion; \"Tested\" is a fact: In professional inventory reporting, \"good\" means the inspector looked at it and it looked okay. It does not mean they turned the heating on, waited for the radiator to get hot, checked for leaks, or bled the air out. I require confirmation that the heating system has been fully serviced and that all radiators are functional. Wall showing visible cracks - wall crack is significant and it is absolutely a landlord's responsibility to address it. That is not a small \"hairline\" crack from a bit of paint drying. But more of a deep, structural-looking crack that runs from the floor up. While some settling cracks in older houses are normal, a crack of that size could indicate movement in the building's foundation or structural wall issues. BEDROOM – FRONT – UPSTAIRS R3.ii Radiators to be tested as not clearly marked as tested anywhere Wall sockets to be tested as not clearly marked as tested anywhere . Thank you for providing the Electrical Installation Condition Report (EICR). I have reviewed this document and note that the electrical installation is rated as 'Satisfactory.' Bathroom/Toilet Glass has condensation what can be done about it? 2. There is visible corrosion and heavy rusting on the shower arm and the flange/escutcheon where it meets the tiled wall The shower arm is heavily corroded, creating a risk of water ingress into the wall structure, which will lead to damp and decay. As this fixture was provided as part of the property, I request that it be replaced to ensure the integrity of the bathroom walls or ameliorate, as to maintain the property in a state of good repair, consistent with the landlord’s obligations. Highlighted in risk of structural damage under , the primary law in England governing a landlord’s repair obligations is Section 11 of the Landlord and Tenant Act 1985 regarding the \"structure and exterior\" and \"sanitary installations.\" Upstairs Corridor This creates an immediate risk of a trip and fall hazard, as there is insufficient landing space to safely exit the room before reaching the stairs. In the UK, staircases and landings are subject to specific safety standards (often referred to as Building Regulations Part K). While older properties may have been built before current regulations were in place, this still fall under the Housing Health and Safety Rating System (HHSRS), which is the framework local councils use to assess if a rental property is safe. A potential hazard The \"400mm Rule\": Current UK building standards typically specify that a door should not swing closer than 400mm to the edge of the first step of a staircase. This is to ensure that a person exiting a room does not immediately step into a void, which is a major cause of serious accidents. Under the Housing Health and Safety Rating System (HHSRS), landlords are required to ensure that properties are free from hazards that could cause harm. Given the severity of this risk, I would like to request that you assess this area and advise on what safety measures can be implemented to mitigate the danger (such as installing a gate, adding clear hazard marking, or changing the door configuration). Bedroom – Walls The inventory notes '6 holes from previous fixtures.' As these are clearly visible and unfinished, please arrange for these to be properly filled and painted to match the rest of the room. This will bring the finish of this room up to the same standard as other areas of the property (such as the bedroom upstairs), which have been appropriately sealed. For consistency and professional standards . Alarms System in the house 609600 289560 0 0 paying for a property that is represented as having certain features. If the alarm is broken or I don't know how to use it, I am not getting what I am paying for, I believe this should be verified for due diligence. As it is listed on the inventory, I require instructions on how to operate it and confirmation that it is in full working order. If it is not intended to be used, please clarify this in writing so it is removed from the list of expected working amenities. As the inventory noted this as 'Unable to verify,' please provide me with the master code and operating instructions so that I can ensure it is in working order and use it to secure the property. Do es agency have the code for the burglar alarm? Conservatory wat to the garden F ormally request a repair to the 'Lean-to' door frame. While the inventory notes that the wood is 'a little rotten,' the actual condition is a significant hole that breaches the frame \r\n",
